items.synopsis: Melbourne will look to recover from defeat to Collingwood in their elimination semifinal against a confident and hungry Carlton. Follow the action in our live blog.

title.children: Blues steady after early goal burst from the Demons

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Good game. Good footy from both teams. Demons got the jump, kicking the first three and rocking the Blues onto the back foot in the early stages. But Carlton settled and responded through Tom De Koning, and some pretty sharp ball movement to get it up there. There are positive signs for both teams, with defences largely holding up and the midfield battle tight. More of the same will do nicely from here. (And yes, the score at the top is currently busted. We're working on it.)
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: QT: Demons lead by seven points, 3.3 (21) to 2.2 (14)

children.content: Good game. Good footy from both teams.

But Carlton settled and responded through Tom De Koning, and some pretty sharp ball movement to get it up there.
There are positive signs for both teams, with defences largely holding up and the midfield battle tight. More of the same will do nicely from here.
(And yes, the score at the top is currently busted. We're working on it.)

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: No late changes. Melbourne had to shuffle the pack a little as Angus Brayshaw is out due to concussion and Jacob van Rooyen is suspended. Michael Hibberd was also omitted. In their place come Adam Tomlison, Charlie Spargo and James Jordon. A couple of forced changes for Carlton too, with Harry McKay concussed and Jack Martin suspended. Matthew Kennedy has been named, and Jesse Motlop comes into the 22 after acting as the Blues' sub last week. The subs tonight are Josh Schache for Melbourne and Oliver Hollands for Carlton. A key forward for the Dees and a runner for the Blues, interesting.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Both these teams have some major changes from the sides that turned out last week. Melbourne's job has become a lot harder with halfback Jahrome Hughes a late scratching after succumbing to a leg injury. Utility Tyran Wishart will start at 7 in 21. Craig Bellamy has also opted to start Bronson Garlick at hooker, with representative star Harry Grant coming off the bench, Queensland Maroons style. Captain Christian Welch is also benched in favour of Nelson Asofa-Solomona. Ryan Papenhuyzen 's broken leg (though not as bad as first thought) obviously has him back on the sidelines, but just minutes before that we also saw Storm winger Xavier Coates go down with an ankle. The good news for the Storm is they get back Justin Olam in the centres to replace Young Tonumaipea, who was targeted by Brisbane. Reimis Smith is also back, although he will move out onto the wing. For the Roosters, they're backline is similarly unrecognisable. Former Storm player Paul Momirovski and Origin rep Corey Allan form a new centre pairing, replacing Joey Manu (hamstring) and Billy Smith (jaw), while Jaxson Paulo will start on the wing in place of Joseph-Aukuso Sua'ali'i (concussion). Up front, Fletcher Baker returns to the bench, with Egan Butcher starting at prop.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Huge ins and outs
